    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1953-10-04T22:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1953-10-04T22:00:00-05:00" n="278"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d278">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">320/10–453: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The United States Representative at the United Nations</hi>
                        (<persName corresp="#p_LODGEHCJ1" type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Lodge</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Department of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">New York</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1953-10-04T22:00:00-05:00"
                            >October 4, 1953—10 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <gloss target="#t_Delga1">Delga</gloss> 63. Reference <gloss target="#t_SC1"
                        >SC</gloss> Elections. Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_MALIKYA1"
                        >Malik</persName> of the <gloss target="#t_USSR1">USSR</gloss> came in to
                    see me this afternoon at his request. He stated that the Security Council
                    elections are on the agenda of tomorrow’s <gloss target="#t_GA1">GA</gloss>
                    plenary and that this is a good time to restore the “gentlemen’s agreement”
                    which was negotiated in London in 1946 regarding the distribution of the six
                    non-permanent seats in the <gloss target="#t_SC1">SC</gloss>. He went on to say
                    that two of the seats, it was then agreed, were to go to Latin America, one to
                    Western Europe, one to the British Commonwealth, one to Eastern Europe and one
                    to the Middle East. To restore this “gentlemen’s agreement”, Mr. <persName
                        corresp="#p_MALIKYA1">Malik</persName> went on to say, would be just and in
                    accordance with the geographical requirement referred to in the Charter.</p>
                <p>I replied that the “gentlemen’s agreement” negotiated in 1946 was in our view an
                    agreement for that year and was not intended to last indefinitely. <persName
                        corresp="#p_WAINHOUSEDW1">Wainhouse</persName> stated that it was
                        <persName>Stevenson</persName> who negotiated this agreement with <persName
                        corresp="#p_GROMYKOAA1">Gromyko</persName> and that Mr.
                        <persName>Stevenson</persName>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d278fn1">
                        <persName>Adlai E. Stevenson</persName>, in 1946 an adviser to the U.S.
                        Delegation to the first part of the First Session of the General Assembly at
                        London.</note> has since confirmed our interpretation with respect to the
                    length of time it was to last.<note n="2" xml:id="d278fn2">For documentation on
                        this question, see <ref target="frus1949v02#pg_265">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1949, vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">ii</hi>, p. 265</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <p>I stated to Mr. <persName corresp="#p_MALIKYA1">Malik</persName> that I was
                    pleased that he came in to talk to me about this; that I would report this
                    conversation at once to the State Department; and that it is our intention to
                    vote for Turkey for that seat.</p>
                <p>Mr. <persName corresp="#p_MALIKYA1">Malik</persName> expressed regret at having
                    to break up my Sunday holiday. I replied that I am always glad to see him, and
                    at any time.</p>
                <p>Mr. <persName corresp="#p_MALIKYA1">Malik</persName> appeared in dark glasses as
                    he entered the building, took them off in the elevator, and put them on again
                    when he left the building.</p>
                <p>As <persName corresp="#p_WAINHOUSEDW1">Wainhouse</persName> escorted <persName
                        corresp="#p_MALIKYA1">Malik</persName> out of the building, the latter
                    inquired about former Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_JESSUPPC1"
                        >Jessup</persName>. 2 Park Avenue, Mr. <persName corresp="#p_MALIKYA1"
                        >Malik</persName> stated, is where he and Ambassador <persName
                        corresp="#p_JESSUPPC1">Jessup</persName> negotiated the Berlin (blockade)
                    agreement.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_LODGEHCJ1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Lodge</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
